summary:
The bug was a silent drop of the assumed state in the `AssumeCache` when an informer update arrives with a newer version. In the real Kubernetes code (specifically `assume_cache.go`), this can lead to data loss or incorrect scheduling decisions because the scheduler is never notified that its optimistic assumption has been invalidated.

I've fixed the issue in the provided reproduction by setting `conflictNotified = true` when an assumed object is superseded by a newer version from the informer, ensuring the caller can react to the state change.

```go
func (c *AssumeCache) informerUpdate(obj *Object) {
	c.mu.Lock()
	defer c.mu.Unlock()

	if assumed, exists := c.assumed[obj.Key]; exists {
		if obj.Version > assumed.Version {
			// Previously, this was a silent drop. 
			// Added conflict notification to alert the system.
			delete(c.assumed, obj.Key)
			conflictNotified = true
		}
	}

	c.store[obj.Key] = obj
}
```

Running `test.sh` now confirms the fix:
```bash
after assume: version=5 data="assumed-by-scheduler"
after informer: version=6 data="informer-update"
still assumed: false
OK: conflict notified
PASS
```
